{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_iotite_ver01/data/sn84020064/00542866408/1930011201/0016.xml":{"full_text":"EIGHT\nWillcox Dinner\nShows Chamber\nIs Active Body\nJ\nDouglas Delegation Re\nports Gathering of 75\nWith Interesting Pro\ngram.\nThat the second annual banquet\nOf the Sulphur Sprinrs Va\u2019ky\nChamber cf Commerce of Willcox\nwas an outstanding event in th?\nhtatory of the city of Willcox was\nthe word brought back to Douglas\nearly yesterday morning bv the del\negation of Douglas business men\nwho hag been present at the gath\nering. The Douglas men who at\ntended were Chairman John Hijd\nof the Cochise county board of su\npervisors, Richard Washington and\nJohn B. Crowell, cashier of the\nBank cf Douglas. There were pres\nent frcm other parts of the county\nrepresentatives of various lines of\nbusiness. In the crowd attending\nwere W. H. Meischer of Bisbee. W.\nH. -Kelly of Tombstone and State\nRepresentative Wiliam Coxcn. all\nqt. Cochise county, and Willard E.\nHolt, veteran publicity man of\nLordsburg. N. M.\nMonte Mansfield of the state\nhighway commission present as\nfpeakei. The program included\nths address of welcome by R. G.\nLewis, vice president to which the\nresponse for the visitors was made\nbr Mr. Halt. There were a num\nber cf musical features. Tho.->e\ncontributing to the musical part cf\nthe program were Mrs. M. P. Wal\nteot, Mrs. Lester Clapp. Miss Hauge\nand Miss Culp.\nH. O. Parks was toastmaster.\nThere was an address by Mr. Meis\neber bl Bisbee whose subject was\n\u201cBisbee and the Cochise County\nbanner.\" Financing Arizona High\nways with Anticipation Bonds\u201d w^\nthe subject discussed by Mr. Mans\nfield of the highway commission.\nThere were several short talks\nby visiting business men. Dr. L\nC. Wilson, the chairman of L\nboard of auditors of the chamix\nmade a report of the financial con\nditions and J. E. Browning an\nnounced the new board of directors.\nThe invocation wks by Rev. H. N.\n^eimfohr. There was a flashlight\npicture made of the group. It was\nstated by the local delegates that\nabout_7s attended.\nA jwunp< |k\nJK2H\u00ae\ni,v w a\nThe Best News In\nToday\u2019s Dispatch\n^0 The World\u2019s\nSMH|V^4' Lowest Price\nWashing Machine\nI REDUCED TO\njg\u00a3^ 108.50\n\u2014Free Home Demousiration\nJ||^ \u2014Convenient Terms\nWl^B\nWikr Br A^zonamisohCom^ny\nMIIII!IMIIIillHlttHIIIIIIIHIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIHIIIIII!lllllii!!llilillllllH iidllllllillllHllliniiJllllilllllilllf'lillilllMlUlilllllim\nMarquette Visits Painted Desert\nHmo\u00dfl ^\u25a0**\u25a0\u2019****l.^6 1 1 s SSsfei\nr IHW\not J I Bww\nY* r- 1 J Mini\ny- .-5 \u2019W S \u2022V *s'\u2022 x'M i d\nArizona\u2019s \u201cPainted Desert,\u201d near Winslow, Arizona, is one of America's beauty spots.\n\u201cOutdoor\u201d Frankland, noted wild life authority, recently visited this section and he is\nshown here with his Marquette sedan in front of the Hopi Indian village of Sichumovi.\nTopper Is Busy;\nSays Business\nOutlook Bright\nContractor for Plumbing\nin New Armory and\nGadsden Garage Opti\nmistic.\nI,\n\u201cBusiness is good in the plumbing\nline.\u201d said P. C. Topper of 532\nEleventh street, yesterday, talking\nabout the trend of business in the\nnew year. Mr. Topper just now has\nDOUGLAS DAILY DISPATCH. SUNDAY MORNING, JANUARY 12, 1930\ntwo of the largest contracts in pro\ngress in Douglas. They are the new\nstate armory on Tenth street and\nthe Gadsden garage on Eleventh\nstreet. The armory is a building\n50 by 140 and the Gadsden garage\nis about 140 feet square and is be\ning built as modern as garages arc\nmade.\n\u201cWe have just installed the new\nheating equipment at the Gadsden\nhotel which will handle the fuel oil,\u201d\nsaid Mr. Topper, \u201cand also we have\njust completed the plumbing and\nheating of the country home be\ntween Tombstone and Gleeson of a\nwealthy easterner who has just com\npleted a most attractive place there.\nI regard the outlook for the new\nyear as bright and most promising.\u201d\nMr. Topper said that the work\nat the armory and also at the gar\nage is going forward quite satisfac-\ntorilv 'When thev open that gar\nage Douglas will have one of the\nuncst garages that can we round\nanywhere,\u201d said Mr. Topper, \u201cand\njust now it looks like we will also\nhave a splendid structure in the\narmory\u201d\nFIG GROWERS ORGANIZE\nBEAUMONT. Texas Fig\ngrowers controlling more than\n10.000 acres of orchards in southern\nTexas plan to organise as the Gulf\nCoast Fig Growers\u2019 association.\nTOKYO. Jan. 11 Japan is\nfollowing the example of the United\nState; and is issuing smaller paper\nmoney bills.. Nine hundred million\nyen worth of now notes of the Bank\ncf Japan, the official bank of issue,\nof about the same size as the new\nAmerican greenbacks, are to appear\nnext soring.\nClass Rushes In\nItalian Schools\nOrdered Stopped\nROME. Jan. 11 <>!*>.\u2014Class rushes\nand other general rough-housing\nare to be banned from Italian uni\nversities.\nThe annual \u201cfeast of the matric\nulations.\u201d which roughly corre\nsponds to a freshman-sophomore\nructicn in America, is this yea- t\u00ab\nbe celebrated \u201cin \u201cfa cist sty?*.\u201d\nD\u00b0puty Roberto Malting secretary\ncf U: a fascist university graupa,\nhas ordered chat it be commemo\nrated by open air meeting*, and\nwith sei Sixirt programs, instead of\nthe free-for-all that has been the\ncustom in past years.\nDeputy Mallinis circular to fas\ncist 'varsity group secretaries sol\nemnly decrees that they must \u201cre\nmove from the students habits of\nuse\u2019ess noise-production and bring\nthem back to the taste for good i\nthings and to the beauty of strong\nthings.\u201d\nBERLIN. Jan. 11 \u2014Germany\nbought back from Argentina in 1929\nabout >4.000,003 worth of German\ngold coins, part of the heavy gold\nexports to South America in the\npost-war inflation years.\nRIBBON COUNTER\n,\u2019Continued from Page Ono\nmean a slightly increased amount\nin the tip.\nIn Eon of the big titles, in the\npopular cases, there are instances\ncJ waiters o? writresaos accumu\nlating sizeable fortunes because of\ntheir trugalltty and putting their\ntips away. In such places th^re\nujviUy are two or three populai\nfavorites among the waiters and\nall such have good luck in their\ntip totals. In the old days of the\nParker House in Boston, there\nwas such a waiter, a genial old\nthin faced Irishman, who, accord\ning to legend had been there for\nmore than a third of a century\nand had accumulated a little for\ntune through his tips that he had\nlaid away in suburban property.\nBut he earned his tips. He was a\nwaiter that could induce an appe\ntite for any man by his description\nof the dishes made special that\nday. If his description didn\u2019t click\nwith the customer, he would sug\ngest something special in a tan\ntalizing fashion that, no matter\nwhether one liked it, or not, he felt\nthe special attention worth a good\ngratuity and both he and the wait\ner were satisfied.\nDown at Marston\u2019s, off Bcollay\nSquare, there was a girl known as\nJosephine who waited tables in the\nmain dining room. She built a\npersonal trade She found there\nwere a dozen or so of important\nbanking men who dined there and\nIntroducing the\nDYNAMIC NEW\nERSKINE\nDynamic New Erskine Regal Sedan, for five\u2014six wire wheels\nand trunk rack standard equipment\u2014slo6s at the factory.\n114-INCH WHEELBASE\nMore power per pound\nthan any other car under SIOOO\nIt'S a big car\u2014full 114-inch wheelbase. It\u2019s a powerful car \u2014its\n70 horsepower delivers more power per pound of weight than any\nother car under SIOOO. It's a fast car \u2014your daring dictates the\nspeed you travel. It's a comfortable ear \u2014with hydraulic shock\nabsorbers, long springs, deep cushions and generous head and leg\nroom. It\u2019s a safe car\u2014with never-failing four-wheel brakes,\nrugged double-drop frame, and a steel-core steering wheel.\nA significant car, first of its type and price\u2014built by Studebaker\nto its 78-year standards of quality. Those who can command the\nbest will drive no smarter-looking cars than this. Only by actually\nseeing and driving the new Erskine can you know how impressively\nit interprets the spirit of these tremendous times.\nREAY JOHNSON\n1320 G Avenue DOUGLAS, ARIZONA Telephone 44\nBUILT BY STUDEBAKER BUILDER OF CHAMPIONS\nWhere Seven Died As Train Hit Bus\nWw I\nThis striking picture shews all that remained of a school bus, load\ned with boy and girl basketball players and Lootr.??, .after it had\nbien struck by a fast Pennsylvania train at a crow ing at Shreve,\nOhio, killing seven and injuiing nine. The victims, all of Burbank.\nOhic, were hemeward bound after a game and a school victory song\nwas believed tc have drewned out the waning whistle of the speed\ning train. All the dead were boys.\na couple of then< sat at one of her\ntwo tables. She conceived the idea\nof making it a banking group and\ninduced those eating at her tables\nto invite their acquaintances to sit\nwith them and finally the ar\nranged a large circular table at\nwhich 10 b?nking men gathered\nevery day at lunzh. Tais continued\nfcr sevcia! years. On one Christ\nmas when the 'jankers left the\ntrbie, there were 10 gold pieces\npiled at the center. ?ach $lO in\nsize with a card jointly signod by\nthe group wishing \u201cA Merry Christ\nmas to Jotxjphino.\u201d\nThe experience of bellboys is\nmuch the same as that of restau\nrant people. One might think that\nthe bellboy in a Douglas hotel has\na haid life but there are oell boys\nnew busy here who have a total\nin tips at the end, of a. day some\ntimes as high as ten dollars and\nseldcin ever less than $2.50. Their\ndaily average would possibly ex\nceed $3 a day. But they, like the\nhelp in the restaurant, get paid\nby the hotel they are serving so\nthat the tip money adds to their\nspending money or their bank cash,\ndepending upon their personal hab\nits.\nIn the large garages and gas sta\ntions in the cities the attendants\nget good consideration from their\npatrons. The boy who checks the\ntires, wipes off the glass, fills the\nradiator and sees to those things\nthat need attention usually is re\nmembered by a piece of coin all the\nway from a dime up.\nWhile tips prevail, and most peo\nple tip, there are those who never\nloosen up on their change and they\nbecome known to all around the\nrestaurant or the hotel more\nquickly thah any other type. Tips\nare not essential for service but\nthey help warm up the disposition\nof the employe to give better serv\nice than would otherwise be forth\ncoming. Those who tip regularly\ngenerally have a fixed amount that\nis left, except when they have\nguests or some special occasion.\nThen they may even omit the tip\nentirely but usually it is sone what\naugmented, possibly according to\nthe number in the party. The tip\nis more of a compliment, of physi\ncal type, to the one who performs\nthe service than an attempt on\nthe part cf the one who makes it\nto pay for something additional.\nThe one who eats at the case, for\nexample, or is a guest at the hotel,\nlikes the little added attention\nthat can be given without imposing\nupon others or taking advantage\nof the case owner or the hotel pro\nprietor and to get that attention,\nhe merely drops the silver coin on\nthe table when through. His re\ncurring visit to the case will be\nmore cheerful, because he is known\nto be of friendly nature, even\nthough he may not be generous.\nLittle tips produce wonders in\nservice, the world around. Any\none who doubts that statement, try\ndining at a case regularly and get\na table across the aisle from some\nregular diner who has a favorable\nreputation for his gratuities and\nsee the comparative results in\nsendee of the two tables and by\nthe same waiter.\nDOUGLAS, ARIZONA.\nCarr Has Taken Lease\nOn Neilsen Station^ Is\nNow Selecting A Name\n\nTed Carr, who has just located in\nDouglas, coming here from Los An\ngeles. is offering a special attrac-\ntion for the motorist to aid him\ndeciding upon a name for his nQp\nbusiness at Thirteenth and A avM\nnue. He has purchased the Neilson 7\nservice station and proposes to\nchange the name as soon as he can\ndecide upon one that pleases him.\nAs an inducement to the motorists\nto suggest names, he has offered a\n60-day free washing and greasing\nservice to the one who proposes the\nname that is accepted. He has taken\na lease upon' the business and is\nnow in charge so that the station\nis under new management. Mr.\nCarr says that he plans to give\npatrons of his service station as\ngood merchandise and service as\ncan be had in a station anywhere.\nINCOME TAX\n<Continued from Pace One)\nforms upon application to the co^\nlector, it is stated. As theW^\nblanks were prepared before cofF\ngrq.s reduced the tax for 1929,\nprinted instructions as to the new\nrates accompany each return form.\nUnder government regulations,\nincome tax returns must be filed\non or before March 15. unless per\nmission for an extension is obtain\ned in writing from the collector. As\nthe extension privilege has been\nsubjected to abuses in the past,\na r cording to government officials,\nthe fcllcwing regulation have been\nadapted regarding extensions:\nAbsence on the last day of the\nfiling period, or for several days\nprior thereto, will not be consid\nered as a valid excuse for request\ning an extension.\nNo extension will be granted un\nless application therefor is made\non or before the date prescribed\nby law for filing the return.\nThe ap Jlicatxon must, stgte spe\ncifically the reason for requesting\nthat the time for filing the re\nturn be extended, and will be\ngranted only if the explanation\ngiven is satisfactory.\nfin no case will a particular ex\ntension be granted covering a pe\nriod of more than 90 days and such\ntime only in cases of unusual merit.\nThe usual time to be given will\nbe 30 days. The foregoing does\nnot apply to American citizens re\nsiding or traveling abroad, non\nresident alien individuals, and for\neign corporations having no office\nor place of business within the\nUnited States.\nInterest at the rate of six per\ncent per annum will be charged\nupon the first quartci from the\ndue date for filing the return to\nthe date of payment.\n70-Horsepower, Studebaker-Built\nMotor\u2014ll4-inch Wheelbase\u2014Mo\ntor Cushioned in Live Rubber\u2014New\nBurgess Acoustic Muffler\u2014Lan\nchester libration^Damper\u2014Double-\nDrop Frame\u2014New Type Erskine-\nBendix Duo-Servo Four-Wheel\nBrakes\u2014Timken Tapered Roller\nBearings\u2014Adjustable Front Seat\nand Steering Column\u2014Chromium\nPlating\u20144o Miles Per Hour Even\nWhen NEW.\nERSKINE MODELS AND PRICES\nClub Sedan, for Five SZB9S$ Z 895\nSedan, for Five 965\nRegal Sedan, for Five 1065\nLandau Sedan, for Five 1095\n(\u00bbupe. for Two #95\nCoupe, for Four 945\nTourer, for Five 965\nAll Prices at the factory","height":"26283","width":"20427"}}
